[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] These events may be happening across the various layers of an organization as sales leads, orders or customer service calls.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] Or, they may be news items, text messages, social media posts, business processes (such as supply chain), traffic reports, weather reports, or other kinds of data.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] An event may also be defined as a "change of state," when a measurement exceeds a predefined threshold of time, temperature, or other value.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] Analysts have suggested that CEP will give organizations a new way to analyze patterns in real-time and help the business side communicate better with IT and service departments.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] CEP has since become an enabling technology in many systems that are used to take immediate action in response to incoming streams of events.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] Applications are now to be found (2018) in many sectors of business including stock market trading systems, mobile devices, internet operations, fraud detection, the transportation industry, and governmental intelligence gathering.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] The vast amount of information available about events is sometimes referred to as the event cloud.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] 2. the appearance of a man in a tuxedo with a woman in a flowing white gown.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] From these events the monitoring system may infer a *complex event*: a wedding.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] CEP as a technique helps discover complex events by analyzing and correlating other events: the bells, the man and woman in wedding attire and the rice flying through the air.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] Commercial applications of CEP exist in variety of industries and include the detection of credit-card fraud, business activity monitoring, and security monitoring.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] The CEP area has roots in discrete event simulation, the active database area and some programming languages.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] The activity in the industry was preceded by a wave of research projects in the 1990s.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] According to the first project that paved the way to a generic CEP language and execution model was the Rapide project in Stanford University, directed by David Luckham.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] In parallel there have been two other research projects: Infospheres in California Institute of Technology, directed by K.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] Mani Chandy, and Apama in University of Cambridge directed by John Bates.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] The commercial products were dependents of the concepts developed in these and some later research projects.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] Community efforts started in a series of event processing symposia organized by the Event Processing Technical Society, and later by the ACM DEBS conference series.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] One of the community efforts was to produce the event processing manifesto.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] CEP is used in operational intelligence (OI) products to provide insight into business operations by running query analysis against live feeds and event data.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] OI collects real-time data and correlates against historical data to provide insight and analysis.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] Multiple sources of data can be combined to provide a common operating picture that uses current information.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] In network management, systems management, application management and service management, people usually refer instead to event correlation.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] As CEP engines, event correlation engines (*event correlators*) analyze a mass of events, pinpoint the most significant ones, and trigger actions.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] However, most of them do not produce new inferred events.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] Instead, they relate high-level events with low-level events.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] Inference engines, e.g., rule-based reasoning engines, typically produce inferred information in artificial intelligence.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] However, they do not usually produce new information in the form of complex (i.e., inferred) events.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] A more systemic example of CEP involves a car, some sensors and various events and reactions.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] Imagine that a car has several sensors—one that measures tire pressure, one that measures speed, and one that detects if someone sits on a seat or leaves a seat.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] In the first situation, the car is moving and the pressure of one of the tires moves from 45 psi to 41 psi over 15 minutes.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] As the pressure in the tire is decreasing, a series of events containing the tire pressure is generated.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] In addition, a series of events containing the speed of the car is generated.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] The car's Event Processor may detect a situation whereby a loss of tire pressure over a relatively long period of time results in the creation of the "lossOfTirePressure" event.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] This new event may trigger a reaction process to note the pressure loss into the car's maintenance log, and alert the driver via the car's portal that the tire pressure has reduced.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] In the second situation, the car is moving and the pressure of one of the tires drops from 45 psi to 20 psi in 5 seconds.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] A different situation is detected—perhaps because the loss of pressure occurred over a shorter period of time, or perhaps because the difference in values between each event were larger than a predefined limit.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] The different situation results in a new event "blowOutTire" being generated.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] This new event triggers a different reaction process to immediately alert the driver and to initiate onboard computer routines to assist the driver in bringing the car to a stop without losing control through skidding.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] In addition, events that represent detected situations can also be combined with other events in order to detect more complex situations.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] For example, in the final situation the car is moving normally and suffers a blown tire which results in the car leaving the road and striking a tree, and the driver is thrown from the car.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] A series of different situations are rapidly detected.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] The combination of "blowOutTire", "zeroSpeed" and "driverLeftSeat" within a very short period of time results in a new situation being detected: "occupantThrownAccident".
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] Even though there is no direct measurement that can determine conclusively that the driver was thrown, or that there was an accident, the combination of events allows the situation to be detected and a new event to be created to signify the detected situation.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] This is the essence of a complex (or composite) event.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] It is complex because one cannot directly detect the situation; one has to infer or deduce that the situation has occurred from a combination of other events.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] A natural fit for CEP has been with business process management (BPM).
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] BPM focuses on end-to-end business processes, in order to continuously optimize and align for its operational environment.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] However, the optimization of a business does not rely solely upon its individual, end-to-end processes.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] Seemingly disparate processes can affect each other significantly.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] Consider this scenario: In the aerospace industry, it is good practice to monitor breakdowns of vehicles to look for trends (determine potential weaknesses in manufacturing processes, material, etc.).
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] Another separate process monitors current operational vehicles' life cycles and decommissions them when appropriate.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] The integration of CEP and BPM must exist at two levels, both at the business awareness level (users must understand the potential holistic benefits of their individual processes) and also at the technological level (there needs to be a method by which CEP can interact with BPM implementation).
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] For a recent state of the art review on the integration of CEP with BPM, which is frequently labeled as Event-Driven Business Process Management, refer to.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] Computation-oriented CEP's role can arguably be seen to overlap with Business Rule technology.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] For example, customer service centers are using CEP for click-stream analysis and customer experience management.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] CEP software can factor real-time information about millions of events (clicks or other interactions) per second into business intelligence and other decision-support applications.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] These "recommendation applications" help agents provide personalized service based on each customer's experience.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] The CEP application may collect data about what customers on the phone are currently doing, or how they have recently interacted with the company in other various channels, including in-branch, or on the Web via self-service features, instant messaging and email.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] The application then analyzes the total customer experience and recommends scripts or next steps that guide the agent on the phone, and hopefully keep the customer happy.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] A time series database is a software system that is optimized for the handling of data organized by time.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] Time series are finite or infinite sequences of data items, where each item has an associated timestamp and the sequence of timestamps is non-decreasing.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] Elements of a time series are often called ticks.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] The timestamps are not required to be ascending (merely non-decreasing) because in practice the time resolution of some systems such as financial data sources can be quite low (milliseconds, microseconds or even nanoseconds), so consecutive events may carry equal timestamps.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] Time series data provides a historical context to the analysis typically associated with complex event processing.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] This can apply to any vertical industry such as finance and cooperatively with other technologies such as BPM.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] The ideal case for CEP analysis is to view historical time series and real-time streaming data as a single time continuum.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] What happened yesterday, last week or last month is simply an extension of what is occurring today and what may occur in the future.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] An example may involve comparing current market volumes to historic volumes, prices and volatility for trade execution logic.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] Or the need to act upon live market prices may involve comparisons to benchmarks that include sector and index movements, whose intra-day and historic trends gauge volatility and smooth outliers.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] Complex event processing is a key enabler in Internet of things (IoT) settings and smart cyber-physical systems (CPS) as well.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] Processing dense and heterogeneous streams from various sensors and matching patterns against those streams is a typical task in such cases.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] The majority of these techniques rely on the fact that representing the IoT system's state and its changes is more efficient in the form of a data stream, instead of having a static, materialized model.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/complex-event-processing] Reasoning over such stream-based models fundamentally differs from traditional reasoning techniques and typically require the combination of model transformations and CEP.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] A **data stream management system** (DSMS) is a computer software system to manage continuous data streams.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] It is similar to a database management system (DBMS), which is, however, designed for static data in conventional databases.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] A DBMS also offers a flexible query processing so that the information needed can be expressed using queries.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] However, in contrast to a DBMS, a DSMS executes a *continuous query* that is not only performed once, but is permanently installed.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] Therefore, the query is continuously executed until it is explicitly uninstalled.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] Since most DSMS are data-driven, a continuous query produces new results as long as new data arrive at the system.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] This basic concept is similar to complex event processing so that both technologies are partially coalescing.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] One important feature of a DSMS is the possibility to handle potentially infinite and rapidly changing data streams by offering flexible processing at the same time, although there are only limited resources such as main memory.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] The following table provides various principles of DSMS and compares them to traditional DBMS.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] One of the biggest challenges for a DSMS is to handle potentially infinite data streams using a fixed amount of memory and no random access to the data.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] There are different approaches to limit the amount of data in one pass, which can be divided into two classes.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] For the one hand, there are compression techniques that try to summarize the data and for the other hand there are window techniques that try to portion the data into (finite) parts.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] The idea behind compression techniques is to maintain only a synopsis of the data, but not all (raw) data points of the data stream.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] The algorithms range from selecting random data points called sampling to summarization using histograms, wavelets or sketching.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] One simple example of a compression is the continuous calculation of an average.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] Instead of memorizing each data point, the synopsis only holds the sum and the number of items.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] The average can be calculated by dividing the sum by the number.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] However, it should be mentioned that synopses cannot reflect the data accurately.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] Thus, a processing that is based on synopses may produce inaccurate results.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] Instead of using synopses to compress the characteristics of the whole data streams, window techniques only look on a portion of the data.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] This approach is motivated by the idea that only the most recent data are relevant.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] Therefore, a window continuously cuts out a part of the data stream, e.g. the last ten data stream elements, and only considers these elements during the processing.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] There are different kinds of such windows like sliding windows that are similar to FIFO lists or tumbling windows that cut out disjoint parts.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] Furthermore, the windows can also be differentiated into element-based windows, e.g., to consider the last ten elements, or time-based windows, e.g., to consider the last ten seconds of data.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] There are also different approaches to implementing windows.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] There are, for example, approaches that use timestamps or time intervals for system-wide windows or buffer-based windows for each single processing step.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] Sliding-window query processing is also suitable to being implemented in parallel processors by exploiting parallelism between different windows and/or within each window extent.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] Since there are a lot of prototypes, there is no standardized architecture.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] However, most DSMS are based on the query processing in DBMS by using declarative languages to express queries, which are translated into a plan of operators.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] These plans can be optimized and executed.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] A query processing often consists of the following steps.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] The formulation of queries is mostly done using declarative languages like SQL in DBMS.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] Since there are no standardized query languages to express continuous queries, there are a lot of languages and variations.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] However, most of them are based on SQL, such as the Continuous Query Language (CQL), StreamSQL and ESP.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] There are also graphical approaches where each processing step is a box and the processing flow is expressed by arrows between the boxes.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] The language strongly depends on the processing model.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] For example, if windows are used for the processing, the definition of a window has to be expressed.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] This stream continuously calculates the average value of "price" of the last 10 tuples, but only considers those tuples whose prices are greater than 100.0.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] In the next step, the declarative query is translated into a logical query plan.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] A query plan is a directed graph where the nodes are operators and the edges describe the processing flow.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] Each operator in the query plan encapsulates the semantic of a specific operation, such as filtering or aggregation.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] In DSMSs that process relational data streams, the operators are equal or similar to the operators of the Relational algebra, so that there are operators for selection, projection, join, and set operations.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] This operator concept allows the very flexible and versatile processing of a DSMS.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] The logical query plan can be optimized, which strongly depends on the streaming model.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] The basic concepts for optimizing continuous queries are equal to those from database systems.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] If there are relational data streams and the logical query plan is based on relational operators from the Relational algebra, a query optimizer can use the algebraic equivalences to optimize the plan.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] These may be, for example, to push selection operators down to the sources, because they are not so computationally intensive like join operators.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] Furthermore, there are also cost-based optimization techniques like in DBMS, where a query plan with the lowest costs is chosen from different equivalent query plans.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] One example is to choose the order of two successive join operators.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] In DBMS this decision is mostly done by certain statistics of the involved databases.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] But, since the data of a data streams is unknown in advance, there are no such statistics in a DSMS.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] However, it is possible to observe a data stream for a certain time to obtain some statistics.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] Using these statistics, the query can also be optimized later.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] So, in contrast to a DBMS, some DSMS allows to optimize the query even during runtime.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] Therefore, a DSMS needs some plan migration strategies to replace a running query plan with a new one.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] Since a logical operator is only responsible for the semantics of an operation but does not consist of any algorithms, the logical query plan must be transformed into an executable counterpart.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] The distinction between a logical and a physical operator plan allows more than one implementation for the same logical operator.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] The join, for example, is logically the same, although it can be implemented by different algorithms like a Nested loop join or a Sort-merge join.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] Notice, these algorithms also strongly depend on the used stream and processing model.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] Finally, the query is available as a physical query plan.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] Since the physical query plan consists of executable algorithms, it can be directly executed.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] For this, the physical query plan is installed into the system.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] The bottom of the graph (of the query plan) is connected to the incoming sources, which can be everything like connectors to sensors.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] The top of the graph is connected to the outgoing sinks, which may be for example a visualization.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] Since most DSMSs are data-driven, a query is executed by pushing the incoming data elements from the source through the query plan to the sink.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream-management-system] Each time when a data element passes an operator, the operator performs its specific operation on the data element and forwards the result to all successive operators.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream] In connection-oriented communication, a **data stream** is the transmission of a sequence of digitally encoded signals to convey information.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream] Typically, the transmitted symbols are grouped into a series of packets.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream] Most data transmitted over the Internet is transmitted as a data stream.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream] Using a mobile phone to have a conversation transmits the sound as a data stream.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream] 2. $\Delta$ is a sequence of positive real time intervals.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream] Data Stream contains different sets of data, that depend on the chosen data format.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream] A **data point** is a tag that collects information about a certain action, performed by a user on a website.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream] Data points exists in two types, the values of which are used to create appropriate audiences.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream] Information gathered out of websites are based on user behavior.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/data-stream] Data providers deliver both personal or non-personal information.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] In computer science, **stream processing** (also known as **event stream processing**, **data stream processing**, or **distributed stream processing**) is a programming paradigm which views streams, or sequences of events in time, as the central input and output objects of computation.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Stream processing encompasses dataflow programming, reactive programming, and distributed data processing.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Stream processing systems use streaming algorithms to trace parallel processing for data streams.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] The stream processing paradigm simplifies parallel software and hardware by restricting the parallel computation that can be performed.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Given a sequence of data (a *stream*), a series of operations (*kernel functions*) is applied to each element in the stream.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Kernel functions are usually pipelined, and optimal local on-chip memory reuse is attempted, in order to minimize the loss in bandwidth, associated with external memory interaction.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] *Uniform streaming*, where one kernel function is applied to all elements in the stream, is typical.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Since the kernel and stream abstractions expose data dependencies, compiler tools can fully automate and optimize on-chip management tasks.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Stream processing hardware can use scoreboarding, for example, to initiate a direct memory access (DMA) when dependencies become known.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] The elimination of manual DMA management reduces software complexity, and an associated elimination for hardware cached I/O, reduces the data area expanse that has to be involved with service by specialized computational units such as arithmetic logic units.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] During the 1980s stream processing was explored within dataflow programming.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] An example is the language SISAL (Streams and Iteration in a Single Assignment Language).
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Stream processing is essentially a compromise, driven by a data-centric model that works very well for traditional DSP or GPU-type applications (such as image, video and digital signal processing) but less so for general purpose processing with more randomized data access (such as databases).
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] By sacrificing some flexibility in the model, the implications allow easier, faster and more efficient execution.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Depending on the context, processor design may be tuned for maximum efficiency or a trade-off for flexibility.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] For each record we can only read from the input, perform operations on it, and write to the output.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] It is permissible to have multiple inputs and multiple outputs, but never a piece of memory that is both readable and writable.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] By way of illustration, the following code fragments demonstrate detection of patterns within event streams.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] The first is an example of processing a data stream using a continuous SQL query (a query that executes forever processing arriving data based on timestamps and window duration).
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] This code fragment illustrates a JOIN of two data streams, one for stock orders, and one for the resulting stock trades.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] The query outputs a stream of all Orders matched by a Trade within one second of the Order being placed.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] The output stream is sorted by timestamp, in this case, the timestamp from the Orders stream.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Another sample code fragment detects weddings among a flow of external "events" such as church bells ringing, the appearance of a man in a tuxedo or morning suit, a woman in a flowing white gown and rice flying through the air.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] A "complex" or "composite" event is what one infers from the individual simple events: a wedding is happening.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Basic computers started from a sequential execution paradigm.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Traditional CPUs are SISD based, which means they conceptually perform only one operation at a time.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] As the computing needs of the world evolved, the amount of data to be managed increased very quickly.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] It was obvious that the sequential programming model could not cope with the increased need for processing power.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Various efforts have been spent on finding alternative ways to perform massive amounts of computations but the only solution was to exploit some level of parallel execution.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] The result of those efforts was SIMD, a programming paradigm which allowed applying one instruction to multiple instances of (different) data.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Most of the time, SIMD was being used in a SWAR environment.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] By using more complicated structures, one could also have MIMD parallelism.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Although those two paradigms were efficient, real-world implementations were plagued with limitations from memory alignment problems to synchronization issues and limited parallelism.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Only few SIMD processors survived as stand-alone components; most were embedded in standard CPUs.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Consider a simple program adding up two arrays containing 100 4-component vectors (i.e.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] This is the sequential paradigm that is most familiar.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Variations do exist (such as inner loops, structures and such), but they ultimately boil down to that construct.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] It assumes the instruction `vector_sum` works.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Although this is what happens with instruction intrinsics, much information is actually not taken into account here such as the number of vector components and their data format.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] You can see however, this method reduces the number of decoded instructions from *numElements * componentsPerElement* to *numElements*.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] The number of jump instructions is also decreased, as the loop is run fewer times.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] These gains result from the parallel execution of the four mathematical operations.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] What happened however is that the packed SIMD register holds a certain amount of data so it's not possible to get more parallelism.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] The speed up is somewhat limited by the assumption we made of performing four parallel operations (please note this is common for both AltiVec and SSE).
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] In this paradigm, the whole dataset is defined, rather than each component block being defined separately.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Describing the set of data is assumed to be in the first two rows.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] After that, the result is inferred from the sources and kernel.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] For simplicity, there's a 1:1 mapping between input and output data but this does not need to be.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Applied kernels can also be much more complex.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] An implementation of this paradigm can "unroll" a loop internally.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] This allows throughput to scale with chip complexity, easily utilizing hundreds of ALUs.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] The elimination of complex data patterns makes much of this extra power available.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] While stream processing is a branch of SIMD/MIMD processing, they must not be confused.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Although SIMD implementations can often work in a "streaming" manner, their performance is not comparable: the model envisions a very different usage pattern which allows far greater performance by itself.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] It has been noted that when applied on generic processors such as standard CPU, only a 1.5x speedup can be reached.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] By contrast, ad-hoc stream processors easily reach over 10x performance, mainly attributed to the more efficient memory access and higher levels of parallel processing.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Although there are various degrees of flexibility allowed by the model, stream processors usually impose some limitations on the kernel or stream size.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] For example, consumer hardware often lacks the ability to perform high-precision math, lacks complex indirection chains or presents lower limits on the number of instructions which can be executed.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Stanford University stream processing projects included the Stanford Real-Time Programmable Shading Project started in 1999.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] A prototype called Imagine was developed in 2002.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] A project called Merrimac ran until about 2004.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] AT&T also researched stream-enhanced processors as graphics processing units rapidly evolved in both speed and functionality.[1] Since these early days, dozens of stream processing languages have been developed, as well as specialized hardware.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] The most immediate challenge in the realm of parallel processing does not lie as much in the type of hardware architecture used, but in how easy it will be to program the system in question in a real-world environment with acceptable performance.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Machines like Imagine use a straightforward single-threaded model with automated dependencies, memory allocation and DMA scheduling.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] This in itself is a result of the research at MIT and Stanford in finding an optimal *layering of tasks* between programmer, tools and hardware.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Programmers beat tools in mapping algorithms to parallel hardware, and tools beat programmers in figuring out smartest memory allocation schemes, etc.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Of particular concern are MIMD designs such as Cell, for which the programmer needs to deal with application partitioning across multiple cores and deal with process synchronization and load balancing.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] A drawback of SIMD programming was the issue of array-of-structures (AoS) and structure-of-arrays (SoA).
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] When multiple of these structures exist in memory they are placed end to end creating an arrays in an *array of structures* (AoS) topology.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] This means that should some algorithm be applied to the location of each particle in turn it must skip over memory locations containing the other attributes.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] If these attributes are not needed this results in wasteful usage of the CPU cache.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Additionally, a SIMD instruction will typically expect the data it will operate on to be contiguous in memory, the elements may also need to be aligned.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] By moving the memory location of the data out of the structure data can be better organised for efficient access in a stream and for SIMD instructions to operate one.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] A *structure of arrays* (SoA), as shown below, can allow this.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Instead of holding the data in the structure, it holds only pointers (memory locations) for the data.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Shortcomings are that if multiple attributes to of an object are to be operated on they might now be distant in memory and so result in a cache miss.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] The aligning and any needed padding lead to increased memory usage.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Overall, memory management may be more complicated if structures are added and removed for example.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] For stream processors, the usage of structures is encouraged.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] From an application point of view, all the attributes can be defined with some flexibility.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Taking GPUs as reference, there is a set of attributes (at least 16) available.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] For each attribute, the application can state the number of components and the format of the components (but only primitive data types are supported for now).
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] The various attributes are then attached to a memory block, possibly defining a *stride* between 'consecutive' elements of the same attributes, effectively allowing interleaved data.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] When the GPU begins the stream processing, it will *gather* all the various attributes in a single set of parameters (usually this looks like a structure or a "magic global variable"), performs the operations and *scatters* the results to some memory area for later processing (or retrieving).
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] More modern stream processing frameworks provide a FIFO like interface to structure data as a literal stream.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] This abstraction provides a means to specify data dependencies implicitly while enabling the runtime/hardware to take full advantage of that knowledge for efficient computation.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] One of the simplest and most efficient stream processing modalities to date for C++, is RaftLib, which enables linking independent compute kernels together as a data flow graph using C++ stream operators.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Apart from specifying streaming applications in high-level languages, models of computation (MoCs) also have been widely used as dataflow models and process-based models.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Historically, CPUs began implementing various tiers of memory access optimizations because of the ever-increasing performance when compared to relatively slow growing external memory bandwidth.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] As this gap widened, big amounts of die area were dedicated to hiding memory latencies.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Since fetching information and opcodes to those few ALUs is expensive, very little die area is dedicated to actual mathematical machinery (as a rough estimation, consider it to be less than 10%).
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] A similar architecture exists on stream processors but thanks to the new programming model, the amount of transistors dedicated to management is actually very little.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Beginning from a whole system point of view, stream processors usually exist in a controlled environment.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] GPUs do exist on an add-in board (this seems to also apply to Imagine).
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] CPUs continue do the job of managing system resources, running applications, and such.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] The stream processor is usually equipped with a fast, efficient, proprietary memory bus (crossbar switches are now common, multi-buses have been employed in the past).
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] The exact amount of memory lanes is dependent on the market range.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] As this is written, there are still 64-bit wide interconnections around (entry-level).
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Most mid-range models use a fast 128-bit crossbar switch matrix (4 or 2 segments), while high-end models deploy huge amounts of memory (actually up to 512 MB) with a slightly slower crossbar that is 256 bits wide.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] By contrast, standard processors from Intel Pentium to some Athlon 64 have only a single 64-bit wide data bus.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Memory access patterns are much more predictable.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] While arrays do exist, their dimension is fixed at kernel invocation.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] The thing which most closely matches a multiple pointer indirection is an *indirection chain*, which is however guaranteed to finally read or write from a specific memory area (inside a stream).
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Because of the SIMD nature of the stream processor's execution units (ALUs clusters), read/write operations are expected to happen in bulk, so memories are optimized for high bandwidth rather than low latency (this is a difference from Rambus and DDR SDRAM, for example).
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] This also allows for efficient memory bus negotiations.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Most (90%) of a stream processor's work is done on-chip, requiring only 1% of the global data to be stored to memory.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] This is where knowing the kernel temporaries and dependencies pays.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Internally, a stream processor features some clever communication and management circuits but what's interesting is the *Stream Register File* (SRF).
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] This is conceptually a large cache in which stream data is stored to be transferred to external memory in bulks.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] As a cache-like software-controlled structure to the various ALUs, the SRF is shared between all the various ALU clusters.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] The key concept and innovation here done with Stanford's Imagine chip is that the compiler is able to automate and allocate memory in an optimal way, fully transparent to the programmer.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] The dependencies between kernel functions and data is known through the programming model which enables the compiler to perform flow analysis and optimally pack the SRFs.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Commonly, this cache and DMA management can take up the majority of a project's schedule, something the stream processor (or at least Imagine) totally automates.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Tests done at Stanford showed that the compiler did an as well or better job at scheduling memory than if you hand tuned the thing with much effort.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] There is proof; there can be a lot of clusters because inter-cluster communication is assumed to be rare.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Internally however, each cluster can efficiently exploit a much lower amount of ALUs because intra-cluster communication is common and thus needs to be highly efficient.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] To keep those ALUs fetched with data, each ALU is equipped with local register files (LRFs), which are basically its usable registers.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] This three-tiered data access pattern, makes it easy to keep temporary data away from slow memories, thus making the silicon implementation highly efficient and power-saving.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Although an order of magnitude speedup can be reasonably expected (even from mainstream GPUs when computing in a streaming manner), not all applications benefit from this.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Communication latencies are actually the biggest problem.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Although PCI Express improved this with full-duplex communications, getting a GPU (and possibly a generic stream processor) to work will possibly take long amounts of time.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] This means it's usually counter-productive to use them for small datasets.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Because changing the kernel is a rather expensive operation the stream architecture also incurs penalties for small streams, a behaviour referred to as the *short stream effect*.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Pipelining is a very widespread and heavily used practice on stream processors, with GPUs featuring pipelines exceeding 200 stages.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] The cost for switching settings is dependent on the setting being modified but it is now considered to always be expensive.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] To avoid those problems at various levels of the pipeline, many techniques have been deployed such as "über shaders" and "texture atlases".
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Those techniques are game-oriented because of the nature of GPUs, but the concepts are interesting for generic stream processing as well.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Most programming languages for stream processors start with Java, C or C++ and add extensions which provide specific instructions to allow application developers to tag kernels and/or streams.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] This also applies to most shading languages, which can be considered stream programming languages to a certain degree.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/event-stream-processing] Commercial implementations are either general purpose or tied to specific hardware by a vendor.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is also used in simulation to mean that the simulation's clock runs at the same speed as a real clock.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Real-time responses are often understood to be in the order of milliseconds, and sometimes microseconds.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] A system not specified as operating in real time cannot usually *guarantee* a response within any timeframe, although *typical* or *expected* response times may be given.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Real-time processing *fails* if not completed within a specified deadline relative to an event; deadlines must always be met, regardless of system load.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] A real-time system has been described as one which "controls an environment by receiving data, processing them, and returning the results sufficiently quickly to affect the environment at that time".
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is used in process control and enterprise systems to mean "without significant delay".
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Real-time software may use one or more of the following: synchronous programming languages, real-time operating systems (RTOSes), and real-time networks.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Each of these provides essential frameworks on which to build a real-time software application.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Systems used for many safety-critical applications must be real-time, such as for control of fly-by-wire aircraft, or anti-lock brakes, both of which demand immediate and accurate mechanical response.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] The term *real-time* derives from its use in early simulation, where a real-world process is simulated at a rate which matched that of the real process (now called real-time simulation to avoid ambiguity).
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Analog computers, most often, were capable of simulating at a much faster pace than real-time, a situation that could be just as dangerous as a slow simulation if it were not also recognized and accounted for.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Minicomputers, particularly from the 1970s onwards, when built into dedicated embedded systems such as DOG (digital on-screen graphic) scanners, increased the need for low-latency priority-driven responses to important interactions with incoming data.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Operating systems such as Data General's RDOS (Real-Time Disk Operating System) and RTOS with background and foreground scheduling as well as Digital Equipment Corporation's RT-11 date from this era.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Background-foreground scheduling allowed low-priority tasks CPU time when no foreground task needed to execute, and gave absolute priority within the foreground to threads/tasks with the highest priority.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Real-time operating systems would also be used for time-sharing multiuser duties.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] For example, Data General Business Basic could run in the foreground or background of RDOS and would introduce additional elements to the scheduling algorithm to make it more appropriate for people interacting via dumb terminals.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Early personal computers were sometimes used for real-time computing.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] The possibility of deactivating other interrupts allowed for hard-coded loops with defined timing, and the low interrupt latency allowed the implementation of a real-time operating system, giving the user interface and the disk drives lower priority than the real-time thread.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] However, several coding libraries exist that offer real-time capabilities in a high-level language on a variety of operating systems, for example, Real-time Java.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Later microprocessors such as the Motorola 68000 and subsequent family members (68010, 68020, ColdFire, etc.) also became popular with manufacturers of industrial control systems.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] This application area is one where real-time control offers genuine advantages in terms of process performance and safety.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] A system is said to be *real-time* if the total correctness of an operation depends not only upon its logical correctness, but also upon the time in which it is performed.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Thus, the goal of a *hard real-time system* is to ensure that all deadlines are met, but for *soft real-time systems* the goal becomes meeting a certain subset of deadlines in order to optimize some application-specific criteria.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] The particular criteria optimized depend on the application, but some typical examples include maximizing the number of deadlines met, minimizing the lateness of tasks and maximizing the number of high-priority tasks meeting their deadlines.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] In the context of multitasking systems the scheduling policy is normally priority driven (pre-emptive schedulers).
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] In some situations, these can guarantee hard real-time performance (for instance, if the set of tasks and their priorities is known in advance).
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] There are other hard real-time schedulers such as rate-monotonic, which is not common in general-purpose systems, as it requires additional information in order to schedule a task: namely, a bound or worst-case estimate for how long the task must execute.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Specific algorithms for scheduling such hard real-time tasks exist, like earliest deadline first, which, ignoring the overhead of context switching, is sufficient for system loads of less than 100%.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] New overlay scheduling systems, such as an adaptive partition scheduler assist in managing large systems with a mixture of hard real-time and non real-time applications.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] In a real-time digital signal processing (DSP) process, the analyzed (input) and generated (output) samples can be processed (or generated) continuously in the time it takes to input and output the same set of samples *independent* of the processing delay.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] It means that the processing delay must be bounded even if the processing continues for an unlimited time.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] The mean processing time per sample, including overhead, is no greater than the sampling period, which is the reciprocal of the sampling rate.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] This is the criterion whether the samples are grouped together in large segments and processed as blocks or are processed individually and whether there are long, short, or non-existent input and output buffers.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Consider an audio DSP example; if a process requires 2.01 seconds to analyze, synthesize, or process 2.00 seconds of sound, it is not real-time.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] However, if it takes 1.99 seconds, it is or can be made into a real-time DSP process.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] A common life analogy is standing in a line or queue waiting for the checkout in a grocery store.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] If the line asymptotically grows longer and longer without bound, the checkout process is not real-time.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] If the length of the line is bounded, customers are being "processed" and output as rapidly, on average, as they are being inputted, then that process *is* real-time.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] The grocer might go out of business or must at least lose business if they cannot make their checkout process real-time; thus, it is fundamentally important that this process is real-time.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] A signal processing algorithm that cannot keep up with the flow of input data, with output falling further and further behind the input, is not real-time.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] If the delay of the output (relative to the input) is bounded regarding a process that operates over an unlimited time, then that signal processing algorithm is real-time, even if the throughput delay may be very long.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Real-time signal processing is necessary, but not sufficient in and of itself, for live signal processing such as what is required in live event support.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Live audio digital signal processing requires both real-time operation and a sufficient limit to throughput delay so as to be tolerable to performers using stage monitors or in-ear monitors and not noticeable as lip sync error by the audience also directly watching the performers.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Tolerable limits to latency for live, real-time processing is a subject of investigation and debate, but is estimated to be between 6 and 20 milliseconds.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Real-time bidirectional telecommunications delays of less than 300 ms ("round trip" or twice the unidirectional delay) are considered "acceptable" to avoid undesired "talk-over" in conversation.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Real-time computing is sometimes misunderstood to be high-performance computing, but this is not an accurate classification.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] For example, a massive supercomputer executing a scientific simulation may offer impressive performance, yet it is not executing a real-time computation.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Conversely, once the hardware and software for an anti-lock braking system have been designed to meet its required deadlines, no further performance gains are obligatory or even useful.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Furthermore, if a network server is highly loaded with network traffic, its response time may be slower, but will (in most cases) still succeed before it times out (hits its deadline).
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Hence, such a network server would not be considered a real-time system: temporal failures (delays, time-outs, etc.) are typically small and compartmentalized (limited in effect), but are not catastrophic failures.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] In a real-time system, such as the FTSE 100 Index, a slowdown beyond limits would often be considered catastrophic in its application context.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] The most important requirement of a real-time system is consistent output, not high throughput.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Some kinds of software, such as many chess-playing programs, can fall into either category.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] For instance, a chess program designed to play in a tournament with a clock will need to decide on a move before a certain deadline or lose the game, and is therefore a real-time computation, but a chess program that is allowed to run indefinitely before moving is not.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] In both of these cases, however, high performance is desirable: the more work a tournament chess program can do in the allotted time, the better its moves will be, and the faster an unconstrained chess program runs, the sooner it will be able to move.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] High performance is indicative of the amount of processing that is performed in a given amount of time, whereas real-time is the ability to get done with the processing to yield a useful output in the available time.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] For example, a near-real-time display depicts an event or situation as it existed at the current time minus the processing time, as nearly the time of the live event.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] The distinction between the terms "near real time" and "real time" is somewhat nebulous and must be defined for the situation at hand.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] The term implies that there are no significant delays.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] In many cases, processing described as "real-time" would be more accurately described as "near real-time".
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Near real-time also refers to delayed real-time transmission of voice and video.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] It allows playing video images, in approximately real-time, without having to wait for an entire large video file to download.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Incompatible databases can export/import to common flat files that the other database can import/export on a scheduled basis so they can sync/share common data in "near real-time" with each other.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Several methods exist to aid the design of real-time systems, an example of which is MASCOT, an old but very successful method that represents the concurrent structure of the system.
[src:stream-processing-concepts/real-time-computing] Other examples are HOOD, Real-Time UML, AADL, the Ravenscar profile, and Real-time Java.
